=== README.md ===
    1: # Distributed Governance Research
    2: 
    3: Research project for developing a functional architecture of distributed governance.
    4: 
    5: The objective of this repository is not to defend a conclusion, but to build a theory through recursive critique: ideas become hypotheses, hypotheses are attacked, surviving hypotheses are refined, and only then are they promoted into the knowledge base.
    6: 
    7: ## Working principle
    8: 
    9: > The goal is not to prove that an idea is correct. The goal is to try to destroy it systematically. If it survives, it may deserve to become theory.
   10: 
   11: ## Repository map
   12: 
   13: ```text
   14: docs/                 Architecture corpus: method, blueprint, citizen flows, diagrams,
   15:                       and the accepted resolution documents (docs/39-113)
   16: knowledge/            Hypotheses (H001-H059), principles (P001-P007), concepts,
   17:                       open questions, and the canonical index (_index.md)
   18: attacks/              Adversarial attack briefs A001-A043 (all resolved)
   19: defenses/             Paired defense briefs D001-D043
   20: contradictions/       Consistency-audit record (C026-C045, all resolved)
   21: drafts/               The working paper (drafts/paper.md, English authoritative;
   22:                       Spanish translation drafts/paper.es.md)
   23: research/             Formal models, simulation results and design, literature map
   24: external-review/      Reviewer packets by profile, English and Spanish
   25: scripts/              Reference checker, Obsidian converter, PDF renderer, and the
   26:                       reproducible allocation simulation
   27: ```
   28: 
   29: ## Current status
   30: 
   31: Working paper v1.13 (working draft; latest deposited version v1.12, DOI 10.5281/zenodo.21252911) with formal mechanism-design propositions and a reproducible 10,000-agent simulation of eight experiments (six with pre-registered designs — the one genuinely *confirmatory* pre-registered test is the later symmetry gate below). NOTE (2026-07-10): a later pre-registered symmetric, selection-only stress test returned NO-GO and **retires the earlier compound value-per-budget multiplier as a calibrated effect** — the distributed selection advantage is real but small (a conditional, stylized-model output — not a calibrated real-world effect and not a validated Core v0 implementation: pre-registered pooled median ~0.025, below its pre-set 0.05 research-program rebuild gate — not a policy-materiality threshold; a post-hoc ratio-of-sums estimate was ~0.026 [0.023, 0.029]); the earlier agent-based figures are kept only as conditional apparatus outputs. The controlling specification is `research/claim-and-estimand-contract.md`. A complete adversarial record: forty-three attack briefs across five rounds (including a five-profile review of the manuscript itself and a final ablation round), each with a paired defense and an accepted resolution — propagated through the corpus for the first four rounds, with the manuscript-review round's D037–D040 propagation tracked. Current phase: post-manuscript consolidation (publication-readiness remediation; see `audits/2026-07-10/remediation-roadmap.md`). The project's origin distillation is preserved in `knowledge/00_SESSION_2026-06-25_DISTILLATION.md`.
   32: 
   33: The satellite computational-experiments program (adversarial architecture ABM, behavioral adoption ABM, planning-vector construction, LLM behavioral calibration — conceived as a second paper) lives in its own repository with full history: [moffermann/distributed-governance-experiments](https://github.com/moffermann/distributed-governance-experiments). It was extracted from this repository's `experiments/` workspace on 2026-07-06; the E8 bridge inputs it generates are committed here as `research/e8-behavioral-inputs.json`.
   34: 
   35: ## License and citation
   36: 
   37: Archived and citable: DOI [10.5281/zenodo.21252911](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21252911) (v1.12, latest deposited version, verified live 2026-07-10) · [10.5281/zenodo.21193846](https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21193846) (concept DOI — always resolves to the latest deposited version). Licensed CC BY 4.0 (all text + research content, including the manuscript) / MIT (code); attribution required. (The live v1.12 record's title string still reads "v1.8"; this can be edited directly in the Zenodo record metadata at any time without a new version/DOI — pending author.)
   38: 
   39: Licensed **CC BY 4.0** for all text and research content (including the working paper, publishable model, and reviewer packets) and **MIT** for code. CC BY attribution is required for the text; the MIT notice must be retained for the code. See `LICENSE.md`. To cite this work, see `CITATION.cff`.
=== RELEASING.md ===
    1: # Release flow (papers → GitHub release → Zenodo)
    2: 
    3: Codified 2026-07-07 after the v1.9 cycle, to keep DOIs from going stale inside deposited PDFs.
    4: 
    5: ## The DOI rule
    6: 
    7: - **Paper headers cite the concept DOI** (`10.5281/zenodo.21193846`): it never changes and always resolves
    8:   to the latest deposited version, so a PDF header can never be stale again. (Single record — the whole
    9:   deposit, corpus + manuscript + code, is CC BY 4.0 / MIT.)
   10: - **Version DOIs** live where they are knowable: CITATION.cff, the GitHub release notes, and the Zenodo record.
   11: - If an exact version DOI inside the PDF is ever wanted, use **pre-reservation**: create the Zenodo new-version *draft first*, read its pre-reserved DOI (`metadata.prereserve_doi`), render the PDFs citing it, upload, then publish. Order: draft → render → upload → publish.
   12: 
   13: ## The version-string rule (anti-recurrence guard for C026)
   14: 
   15: Whenever the **draft** version changes (the `drafts/paper.md` header), **immediately** sync the version *strings* in `CITATION.cff` (`version`), `.zenodo.json` (`version` + title suffix), and `README.md` — even between deposits, with Zenodo paused. The metadata version string must never lag the draft. (DOIs are separate: headers cite the concept DOI; version DOIs are only swept on an actual deposit.) This drift recurred at v1.8→v1.12 (2026-07-10) exactly because the draft moved without a deposit.
   16: 
   17: ## License note (author decision, 2026-07-10)
   18: 
   19: The whole deposit is **CC BY 4.0** for all text and research content (corpus + manuscript) and **MIT** for
   20: code — a single record, one concept-DOI lineage (`10.5281/zenodo.21193846`; latest version
   21: `10.5281/zenodo.21252911` = v1.12). CC BY attribution applies to text/research content; MIT requires notice retention for code. (An earlier plan to protect the
   22: manuscript under CC BY-NC-ND with a separate record was dropped: the code/corpus are already public, so a
   23: protected manuscript would not have protected the implementation, and the author chose full openness.)
   24: 
   25: ## The cycle
   26: 
   27: 1. Edit `drafts/paper.md` and mirror in `drafts/paper.es.md` (English is authoritative).
   28: 2. `npm run check-anchors` clean.
   29: 3. Render four outputs with `scripts/md-to-pdf.mjs` (`--lang en|es`, `--toc`, `--html` for the screen-reader edition); rasterize a few pages (PyMuPDF) and inspect them before shipping.
   30: 4. Commit, tag `vX.Y`, `gh release create` with the four renders attached.
   31: 5. Zenodo new version on the deposition id in `_backups/zenodo-depid.txt` (a non-secret id). **Supply the API token through an environment variable at deposit time — `ZENODO_TOKEN`, exported into the shell session only (read it from your OS credential store / password manager) — never a token file left in the repo tree.** New-version draft → replace files (corpus + manuscript renders + code) → bump `version`/`publication_date` → publish → update the depid file.
   32: 6. Sweep the *version* DOI across CITATION.cff/README notes (headers stay on the concept DOI).
   33: 
   34: ## Credential handling (security)
   35: 
   36: The Zenodo API token is a release-account credential: treat it as a secret.
   37: - **Never persist it to a file in the working tree** (an earlier version of this flow named `_backups/zenodo-token.txt`; that pattern is retired). Pass it via `ZENODO_TOKEN` in the shell session, or a protected CI secret if the deposit is ever automated.
   38: - `_backups/` is git-ignored so a stray credential there can never be committed, but git-ignore is not protection: **if a `zenodo-token.txt` was ever created, delete it and rotate the token** in the Zenodo account settings.
   39: - Scope the token to the minimum needed (`deposit:write`, `deposit:actions`).
